1. ANSI-SPARC Architecture

Definition:

ANSI-SPARC Architecture is a three-schema architecture proposed by the ANSI-SPARC committee that separates the database into External, Conceptual, and Internal levels to achieve data abstraction and data independence.

2. External Level (View Level)

Definition:

The External Level is the highest level of database abstraction that describes the part of the database that a particular user or group of users can access.

Key Points
User-specific view
Multiple external views possible
Provides security and data hiding
3. Conceptual Level (Logical Level)

Definition:

The Conceptual Level describes the complete logical structure of the entire database, including entities, attributes, relationships, and constraints, independent of physical storage details.

Key Points
Represents the whole database
Defines tables and relationships
Hides physical storage details
4. Internal Level (Physical Level)

Definition:

The Internal Level is the lowest level of database abstraction that describes how data is physically stored in the database, including file organization, indexes, and storage structures.

Key Points
Physical storage details
File structures
Indexes and access paths

5. External Schema

Definition:

An External Schema is the description of a database as seen by a particular user or user group.

6. Conceptual Schema

Definition:

A Conceptual Schema is the overall logical description of the entire database.

7. Internal Schema

Definition:

An Internal Schema is the description of the physical storage structure of the database.

8. Data Abstraction

Definition:

Data Abstraction is the process of hiding unnecessary details from users and showing only the essential information.

9. Data Independence

Definition:

Data Independence is the ability to modify a schema at one level of the database system without affecting the schema at the next higher level.

10. Physical Data Independence

Definition:

Physical Data Independence is the ability to change the internal schema without affecting the conceptual schema.

Example
Adding an index
Changing file organization
Changing storage location

No change required in tables or applications.

11. Logical Data Independence

Definition:

Logical Data Independence is the ability to change the conceptual schema without affecting the external schemas or application programs.

Example
Adding a new attribute
Adding a new table
Modifying relationships

User views remain unchanged.

12. External-Conceptual Mapping

Definition:

External-Conceptual Mapping defines the relationship between an external schema and the conceptual schema.

13. Conceptual-Internal Mapping

Definition:

Conceptual-Internal Mapping defines the relationship between the conceptual schema and the internal schema.

Interview One-Liner Answers
What is External Level?

The External Level describes how individual users view the database.

What is Conceptual Level?

The Conceptual Level describes the complete logical structure of the database.

What is Internal Level?

The Internal Level describes how data is physically stored in the database.

What is Data Independence?

Data Independence is the ability to change one schema level without affecting the next higher level.

What is Physical Data Independence?

Changing the internal schema without affecting the conceptual schema.

What is Logical Data Independence?

Changing the conceptual schema without affecting external schemas.

